Reasoning:
I will prioritize maritime control and flexible posture rather than an early continental commitment. Occupying the Channel (F LON -> ENG) secures our most vital sealanes into the Atlantic and protects London/Liverpool shipping; it also communicates clearly to France that we respect our channel understanding by taking the agreed defensive position rather than contesting Brest. Projecting a fleet into the North Sea (F EDI -> NTH) provides presence to deter or contest German movements from Kie/Denmark, shaping German calculations without committing an army on the continent. Moving Liverpool to Yorkshire (A LVP -> YOR) secures our northern coast, preserves the option to shift forces to Scotland or support northern naval operations next turn, and keeps our army flexible to counter a German naval incursion.

I do not issue inter-unit supports this turn because occupying ENG and NTH is the priority for sealanes; attempting to support one fleet would force another to remain idle or relinquish a strategic square. If Germany nonetheless pushes Kie->NTH, the likely result is a bounce (no German army support to that sea), and I will immediately seek French and Russian cooperation to reinforce the North Sea and punish German naval overreach. This set of moves keeps our options open, maximizes naval leverage, and preserves the balance‑of‑power incentive for allies to work with us rather than against us.

